<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900723-0006</DOCNO><DOCID>900723-0006.</DOCID><HL>   Technology:   Stardent Computer   Fires Co-Chairmen   In Wake of Suit</HL><DATE>07/23/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><CO>   KUB WNEWS</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><LP>   NEWTON, Mass. -- Stardent Computer Inc. said its board ofdirectors voted to fire Allen H. Michels and Matthew Sandersas the company's co-chairmen in the wake of their lawsuitagainst Kubota Corp., Stardent's largest investor.   Messrs. Michels and Sanders remain directors of Stardentunder the company's by-laws, although they lose theco-chairman title. The two men, who co-founded ArdentComputer Corp., one of the two firms that were merged to formStardent, hadn't been active in operations.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;Our terminations are unlawful and retaliatory,&quot; Mr.Michels and Mr. Sanders said in a written statement. &quot;Thiscompounds the illegal acts alleged in our complaint and weplan to seek immediate redress in the courts.&quot;   Messrs. Michels and Sanders have sued Kubota for $25million in damages, charging that the Japanese tractor makerhad conspired to fraudulently obtain Stardent's technology.   Stardent said that a special board committee formed toinvestigate the lawsuit &quot;found the claims to be withoutmerit.&quot;   Stardent also said that Kubota agreed to invest up to $50million more in Stardent over the next two years in a seriesof transactions that could boost its stake to as much as 30%from the 22% it holds currently. Kubota has already investedabout $100 million in the company, a maker of graphicssupercomputers.   In addition, Stardent said, Kubota will take overcontinuing development of Stardent's current computer line aswell as final assembly and testing. Those functions had beendone at Stardent's Sunnyvale, Calif. facilities. Kubotaalready makes the computers in Japan. Stardent will remainresponsible for marketing the products and will develop a newproduct line.   A spokeswoman said that of roughly 100 Stardent workers inSunnyvale, about 75 will be offered jobs by Kubota and mostof the rest will be offered jobs at other Stardentfacilities.</TEXT></DOC>